Class Topic.Subscribe<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.apache.beam.sdk.transforms.PTransform<PBegin,PCollection<T>>
      • com.ibm.streams.beam.sdk.io.Topic.Subscribe<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The tuple type to be subscribed.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, HasDisplayData
    Enclosing class:
    Topic

    public static class Topic.Subscribe<T>
extends PTransform<PBegin,PCollection<T>>
    A Subscribe transform reads from streams published by other IBM Streams or Beam applications and creates a PCollection.

    To be compatible with non-Beam applications, the subscribed streams offer no watermarks. To reconstruct watermarks, users could use the withWatermarkFn(SerializableFunction) API to provide a function to extract watermarks from the input data type T.

    Below is an minimum example to subscribe from a long topic: 

    
 p.apply(Subscribe.ofType(Long.class)
                  .from(topic));

    Subscribe transform imports a stream into a Beam pipeline. From Beam's perspective, it is the same as a Source transform, so applications are allowed to control timestamps and watermarks. The Subscribe transform takes two required parameters and three optional parameters:

    • (Required) from(String) specifies the topic to subscribe from.
    • (Required) ofType(Class) or ofType(TypeDescriptor) specifies the subscribed data type. The latter supports nested generic types, such as TypeDescriptor<KV<Long, Long>>. The subscribed data class must be serializable.
    • (Optional) withTimestampFn(SerializableFunction) provides a function to extract timestamps from the subscribed data stream. If absent, timestamps of all tuples will be set to BoundedWindow.TIMESTAMP_MIN_VALUE.
    • (Optional) withWatermarkFn(SerializableFunction) provides a function to create watermarks from the subscribed data stream. If absent, Subscribe will use withTimestampFn(SerializableFunction).
    • (Optional) setCoder(Coder) provides the element coder. If absent, the transform will try to infer the coder from Beam's coder registry.

      • from

        public Topic.Subscribe<T> from(String topic)
        Sets the topic to subscribe from.
        Subscribers are matched to published streams when
        • topic is a match (wildcard matching is supported), and
        • the type of the stream T is an exact match.

        Publish-subscribe is a many-to-many relationship, multiple streams from multiple applications may be published on the same topic and type. Multiple subscribers may subscribe to a topic and type.
        A subscription will match all publishers using the same topic and tuple type. Tuples on the published streams will appear on the returned stream, as a single stream.
        The subscription is dynamic. The returned stream will subscribe to a matching stream published by a newly submitted application (a job), and stops a subscription when a running job is cancelled.

        Publish-subscribe only works when the pipeline is submitted with DISTRIBUTED or STREAMING_ANALYTICS_SERVICE contexts. This allows different applications (or even within the same application) to communicate using published streams.

        Parameters:
        topic - the topic to subscribe from.
